land, Suffolk, England":"Stoke by Nayland, Suffolk, England","Essex, England":"Essex, England"},"nl":{"1495–1554":"1495–1554","1497–1572":"1497–1572","1520–1586":"1520–1586","1544–Male":"1544–Overleden","1548–1574":"1548–1574","1450–1543":"1450–1543","1480–1523":"1480–1523","1495":"1495","1572":"1572","1450":"1450","1480":"1480","1523":"1523","1511":"1511","1544":"1544","1543":"1543","1554":"1554","about 1548":"circa 1548","1586":"1586","1520":"1520","1574":"1574","1497":"1497","about 1544":"circa 1544","3 December 1520":"3 december 1520","about 1493":"circa 1493","1549":"1549","1548":"1548","Stoke, Nayland, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Stoke by Ipswich, Suffolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Nayland, Suffolk, England":"Nayland, Suffolk, England","Stoke by Nayland, Suffolk, England":"Stoke by Nayland, Suffolk, England","Essex, England":"Essex, England"},"en":{"1495–1554":"1495–1554","1497–1572":"1497–1572","1520–1586":"1520–1586","1544–Male":"1544–Deceased","1548–1574":"1548–1574","1450–1543":"1450–1543","1480–1523":"1480–1523","1495":"1495","1572":"1572","1450":"1450","1480":"1480","1523":"1523","1511":"1511","1544":"1544","1543":"1543","1554":"1554","about 1548":"about 1548","1586":"1586","1520":"1520","1574":"1574","1497":"1497","about 1544":"about 1544","3 December 1520":"3 December 1520","about 1493":"about 1493","1549":"1549","1548":"1548","Stoke, Nayland, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Stoke by Ipswich, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","Nayland, Suffolk, England":"Nayland, Suffolk, England","Stoke by Nayland, Suffolk, England":"Stoke by Nayland, Suffolk, England","Essex, England":"Essex, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Abbes","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Arabic/Muslim Syed, Ghulam, Ali, Mohammad, Mohammed, Mohamed, Farhat, Abbas, Asad, Azhar, Ahmad, Amir.","Muslim: from the Arabic personal name <i>ʿAbbās</i>, literally ‘stern, austere’. Al-ʿAbbas ibn ʿAbd al-Muttalib was the name of an uncle of the prophet Muhammad (see   Abbasi  ).","Dutch: patronymic from the personal name <i>Abbe</i>, a pet form of   Albert   or   Albrecht  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Abbasi","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Arabic/Muslim Mohammad, Ali, Abdul, Adnan, Tariq, Arshad, Mahmood, Mohammed, Mousa, Muhammad, Nadeem, Sami.","Muslim (Indian subcontinent and Iran): surname denoting descent from or association with someone called   Abbas  , in particular association with Al-‘Abbas ibn ‘Abd al-Muttalib, an uncle (died 652) of the prophet Muhammad, the ancestor of the Abbasid dynasty of caliphs, who ruled the Islamic world from 750 to 1258."]},{"name":"Abas","meanings":["Muslim: variant of   Abbas  ."]}]},{"name":"George","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Via Old French and Latin, from Greek <i>Georgios</i> (a derivative of <i>geōrgos</i> ‘farmer’, from <i>gē</i> ‘earth’ + <i>ergein</i> ‘to work’). This was the name of several early saints, including the shadowy figure who is now the patron of England (as well as of Germany and Portugal). If the saint existed at all, he was perhaps martyred in Palestine in the persecutions of Christians instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  at the beginning of the 4th century. The popular legend in which the hero slays a dragon is a medieval Italian invention. He was for a long time a more important saint in the Orthodox Church than in the West, and the name was not much used in England during the Middle Ages, even after  St George  came to be regarded as the patron of England in the 14th century. Its use increased from the 1400s, and by  1500  it was regularly among the most popular male names. This popularity was reinforced when  George I  came to the throne in  1714 , bringing this name with him from Germany. It has been one of the most popular English boys' names ever since."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":54,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When George Abbes was born in 1495, in Nayland, Suffolk, England, his father, David Abbes, was 45 and his mother, Elizabeth Goodwyn, was 15. He married Elizabeth Ehler Goodwyn in 1511, in Nayland, Suffolk, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 2 daughters. He died in 1554, in Stoke by Ipswich, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 59."},"et":{"1495–1554":"1495–1554","1497–1572":"1497–1572","1520–1586":"1520–1586","1544–Male":"1544–Surnud","1548–1574":"1548–1574","1450–1543":"1450–1543","1480–1523":"1480–1523","1495":"1495","1572":"1572","1450":"1450","1480":"1480","1523":"1523","1511":"1511","1544":"1544","1543":"1543","1554":"1554","about 1548":"umbes 1548","1586":"1586","1520":"1520","1574":"1574","1497":"1497","about 1544":"umbes 1544","3 December 1520":"3. detsember 1520","about 1493":"umbes 1493","1549":"1549","1548":"1548","Stoke, Nayland, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Stoke by Ipswich, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Nayland, Suffolk, England":"Nayland, Suffolk, England","Stoke by Nayland, Suffolk, England":"Stoke by Nayland, Suffolk, England","Essex, England":"Essex, England"},"fi":{"1495–1554":"1495–1554","1497–1572":"1497–1572","1520–1586":"1520–1586","1544–Male":"1544–Kuollut","1548–1574":"1548–1574","1450–1543":"1450–1543","1480–1523":"1480–1523","1495":"1495","1572":"1572","1450":"1450","1